# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: american-welding-society
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:american-welding-society/american-institute-of-steel-construction] The **American Institute of Steel Construction** (**AISC**) is a not-for-profit technical institute and trade association for the use of structural steel in the construction industry of the United States.
[src:american-welding-society/american-institute-of-steel-construction] AISC publishes the Steel Construction Manual, an authoritative volume on steel building structure design that is referenced in all U.S. building codes.
[src:american-welding-society/american-institute-of-steel-construction] The organization works with government agencies, policymakers, and other stakeholders to promote policies and regulations that support the industry's growth and development.
[src:american-welding-society/american-institute-of-steel-construction] In 1911, two civil engineering organizations, the Bridge Builders Society and the Structural Steel Society, began cooperating to form broad codes of ethics and practices within the profession.
[src:american-welding-society/american-institute-of-steel-construction] In 1917, during World War I, the two groups merged into the **War Service Committee** which helped procure fabricated structural steel and coordinate industry efforts.
[src:american-welding-society/american-institute-of-steel-construction] According to the AISC, the *Steel Construction Manual* is the "premier reference for structural steel design and construction in the United States" having been published since 1927.
[src:american-welding-society/american-institute-of-steel-construction] Editions are usually made every five to six years to keep up with developments in structural steel codes and standards and to incorporate new materials.
[src:american-welding-society/american-national-standards-institute] The **American National Standards Institute** (**ANSI**) is a private nonprofit organization that oversees the development of voluntary consensus standards for products, services, processes, systems, and personnel in the United States.
[src:american-welding-society/american-national-standards-institute] The organization also coordinates U.S. standards with international standards so that American products can be used worldwide.
[src:american-welding-society/american-national-standards-institute] ANSI accredits standards that are developed by representatives of other standards organizations, government agencies, consumer groups, companies, and others.
[src:american-welding-society/american-national-standards-institute] These standards ensure that the characteristics and performance of products are consistent, that people use the same definitions and terms, and that products are tested the same way.
[src:american-welding-society/american-national-standards-institute] ANSI also accredits standards developing organizations (SDOs) and provides a searchable directory of accredited standards developers (ASDs).
[src:american-welding-society/american-national-standards-institute] ANSI similarly accredits organizations that carry out product or personnel certification in accordance with requirements defined in international standards.
[src:american-welding-society/american-national-standards-institute] The organization's headquarters are in Washington, D.C.
[src:american-welding-society/american-national-standards-institute] ANSI's operations office is located in New York City.
[src:american-welding-society/american-national-standards-institute] The ANSI annual operating budget is funded by the sale of publications, membership dues and fees, accreditation services, fee-based programs, and international standards programs.
[src:american-welding-society/american-national-standards-institute] Many ANSI regulations are incorporated by reference into United States federal statutes (i.e. by OSHA regulations referring to individual ANSI specifications).
[src:american-welding-society/american-national-standards-institute] ANSI does not make these standards publicly available, and charges money for access to these documents; it further claims that it is copyright infringement for them to be provided to the public by others free of charge.
[src:american-welding-society/american-national-standards-institute] These assertions have been the subject of criticism and litigation.
[src:american-welding-society/american-national-standards-institute] ANSI was most likely formed in 1918, when five engineering societies and three government agencies founded the **American Engineering Standards Committee** (**AESC**).
[src:american-welding-society/american-national-standards-institute] In 1928, the AESC became the **American Standards Association** (**ASA**).
[src:american-welding-society/american-national-standards-institute] In 1966, the ASA was reorganized and became the **United States of America Standards Institute** (**USASI**).
[src:american-welding-society/american-national-standards-institute] In February 1969, Ralph Nader harshly criticized the USASI in public remarks as "manifestly deceptive" in several different ways.
[src:american-welding-society/american-national-standards-institute] He specifically attacked the name USASI as improperly implying some kind of official connection with the federal government of the United States.
[src:american-welding-society/american-national-standards-institute] had been members of the United Engineering Society (UES).
[src:american-welding-society/american-national-standards-institute] At the behest of the AIEE, they invited the U.S. government Departments of War, Navy (combined in 1947 to become the Department of Defense or DOD) and Commerce to join in founding a national standards organization.
[src:american-welding-society/american-national-standards-institute] According to Adam Stanton, the first permanent secretary and head of staff in 1919, AESC started as an ambitious program and little else.
[src:american-welding-society/american-national-standards-institute] Staff for the first year consisted of one executive, Clifford B.
[src:american-welding-society/american-national-standards-institute] LePage, who was on loan from a founding member, ASME.
[src:american-welding-society/american-national-standards-institute] An annual budget of $7,500 was provided by the founding bodies.
[src:american-welding-society/american-national-standards-institute] In 1931, the organization (renamed ASA in 1928) became affiliated with the U.S.
[src:american-welding-society/american-national-standards-institute] National Committee of the International Electrotechnical Commission (IEC), which had been formed in 1904 to develop electrical and electronics standards.
[src:american-welding-society/american-national-standards-institute] ANSI's members are government agencies, organizations, academic and international bodies, and individuals.
[src:american-welding-society/american-national-standards-institute] In total, the Institute represents the interests of more than 270,000 companies and organizations and 30 million professionals worldwide.
[src:american-welding-society/american-national-standards-institute] ANSI's market-driven, decentralized approach has been criticized in comparison with more planned and organized international approaches to standardization.
[src:american-welding-society/american-national-standards-institute] Although ANSI itself does not develop standards, the Institute oversees the development and use of standards by accrediting the procedures of standards developing organizations.
[src:american-welding-society/american-national-standards-institute] ANSI accreditation signifies that the procedures used by standards developing organizations meet the institute's requirements for openness, balance, consensus, and due process.
[src:american-welding-society/american-national-standards-institute] ANSI also designates specific standards as American National Standards, or ANS, when the Institute determines that the standards were developed in an environment that is equitable, accessible and responsive to the requirements of various stakeholders.
[src:american-welding-society/american-national-standards-institute] Voluntary consensus standards quicken the market acceptance of products while making clear how to improve the safety of those products for the protection of consumers.
[src:american-welding-society/american-national-standards-institute] There are approximately 9,500 American National Standards that carry the ANSI designation.
[src:american-welding-society/american-national-standards-institute] The institute is the official U.S. representative to the two major international standards organizations, the International Organization for Standardization (ISO), as a founding member, and the International Electrotechnical Commission (IEC), via the U.S.
[src:american-welding-society/american-national-standards-institute] ANSI participates in almost the entire technical program of both the ISO and the IEC, and administers many key committees and subgroups.
[src:american-welding-society/american-national-standards-institute] In many instances, U.S. standards are taken forward to ISO and IEC, through ANSI or the USNC, where they are adopted in whole or in part as international standards.
[src:american-welding-society/american-national-standards-institute] Adoption of ISO and IEC standards as American standards increased from 0.2% in 1986 to 15.5% in May 2012.
[src:american-welding-society/american-national-standards-institute] Each of the panels works to identify, coordinate, and harmonize voluntary standards relevant to these areas.
[src:american-welding-society/american-national-standards-institute] In 2009, ANSI and the National Institute of Standards and Technology (NIST) formed the Nuclear Energy Standards Coordination Collaborative (NESCC).
[src:american-welding-society/american-national-standards-institute] NESCC is a joint initiative to identify and respond to the current need for standards in the nuclear industry.
[src:american-welding-society/american-society-of-mechanical-engineers] Founded as an engineering society focused on mechanical engineering in North America, ASME is today multidisciplinary and global.
[src:american-welding-society/american-society-of-mechanical-engineers] ASME has over 85,000 members in more than 135 countries worldwide.
[src:american-welding-society/american-society-of-mechanical-engineers] ASME was founded in 1880 in response to numerous steam boiler pressure vessel failures by Alexander Lyman Holley, Henry Rossiter Worthington, John Edison Sweet and Matthias N.
[src:american-welding-society/american-society-of-mechanical-engineers] Forney, with Robert Henry Thurston as the society's founding president.
[src:american-welding-society/american-society-of-mechanical-engineers] Known for setting codes and standards for mechanical devices, ASME conducts one of the world's largest technical publishing operations.
[src:american-welding-society/american-society-of-mechanical-engineers] It holds numerous technical conferences and hundreds of professional development courses each year and sponsors numerous outreach and educational programs.
[src:american-welding-society/american-society-of-mechanical-engineers] Ned Djilali and Georgia Tech president and woman engineer supporter Blake R Van Leer were executive members.
[src:american-welding-society/american-society-of-mechanical-engineers] Kate Gleason and Lydia Weld were the first two women members.
[src:american-welding-society/american-society-of-mechanical-engineers] ASME is one of the oldest standards-developing organizations in America.
[src:american-welding-society/american-society-of-mechanical-engineers] It produces approximately 600 codes and standards covering many technical areas, such as fasteners, plumbing fixtures, elevators, pipelines, and power plant systems and components.
[src:american-welding-society/american-society-of-mechanical-engineers] ASME's standards are developed by committees of subject matter experts using an open, consensus-based process.
[src:american-welding-society/american-society-of-mechanical-engineers] Many ASME standards are cited by government agencies as tools to meet their regulatory objectives.
[src:american-welding-society/american-society-of-mechanical-engineers] ASME standards are therefore voluntary, unless the standards have been incorporated into a legally binding business contract or incorporated into regulations enforced by an authority having jurisdiction, such as a federal, state, or local government agency.
[src:american-welding-society/american-society-of-mechanical-engineers] ASME's standards are used in more than 100 countries and have been translated into numerous languages.
[src:american-welding-society/american-society-of-mechanical-engineers] The largest ASME standard, both in size and in the number of volunteers involved in its preparation, is the ASME Boiler and Pressure Vessel Code (BPVC).
[src:american-welding-society/american-society-of-mechanical-engineers] The BPVC provides rules for the design, fabrication, installation, inspection, care, and use of boilers, pressure vessels, and nuclear components.
[src:american-welding-society/american-society-of-mechanical-engineers] The code also includes standards on materials, welding and brazing procedures and qualifications, nondestructive examination, and nuclear in-service inspection.
[src:american-welding-society/american-society-of-mechanical-engineers] In addition to academic journals, since 1880 the ASME has also published the magazine *Mechanical Engineering*.
[src:american-welding-society/american-society-of-mechanical-engineers] This means the nominees need not be professional educators.
[src:american-welding-society/american-society-of-mechanical-engineers] (1879–1964), an ASME Member and professor of mechanical engineering and head of the department at the Polytechnic Institute of Brooklyn, established the Medal.
[src:american-welding-society/american-society-of-mechanical-engineers] ASME runs several annual E-Fests, or Engineering Festivals, taking the place of the Student Professional Development Conference (SPDC) series.
[src:american-welding-society/american-society-of-mechanical-engineers] In addition to the Human Powered Vehicle Challenge (HPVC), the Innovative Additive Manufacturing 3D Challenge (IAM3D), the Student Design Competition, and the Old Guard Competition, there are also talks, interactive workshops, and entertainment.
[src:american-welding-society/american-society-of-mechanical-engineers] These events allows students to network with working engineers, host contests, and promote ASME's benefits to students as well as professionals.
[src:american-welding-society/american-society-of-mechanical-engineers] E-Fests are held in four regions in the United States and internationally—western U.S, eastern U.S., Asia Pacific, and South America—with the E-Fest location for each region changing every year.
[src:american-welding-society/american-society-of-mechanical-engineers] ASME holds a variety of competitions every year for engineering students from around the world.
[src:american-welding-society/american-society-of-mechanical-engineers] ASME has four key offices in the United States, including its headquarters operation in New York, N.Y., and three international offices in Beijing, China; Brussels, Belgium, and New Delhi, India.
[src:american-welding-society/american-society-of-mechanical-engineers] ASME has two institutes and 32 technical divisions within its organizational structure.
[src:american-welding-society/american-society-of-mechanical-engineers] In 1982, ASME was found to be the first non-profit organization to in violation of the Sherman Antitrust Act.
[src:american-welding-society/american-society-of-mechanical-engineers] The United States Supreme Court found the organization liable for more than $6 million in *American Society of Mechanical Engineers v.
[src:american-welding-society/american-welding-society] The **American Welding Society** (AWS) was founded in 1919 as a non-profit organization to advance the science, technology and application of welding and allied joining and cutting processes, including brazing, soldering and thermal spraying.
[src:american-welding-society/american-welding-society] Headquartered in Doral, Florida, and led by a volunteer organization of officers and directors, AWS serves over 73,000 members worldwide and is composed of 22 Districts with 250 Sections and student chapters.
[src:american-welding-society/american-welding-society] The roots of the American Welding Society stretch back to World War I, when the sudden demands of swiftly producing military equipment brought about the need for standardization of the manufacturing industry.
[src:american-welding-society/american-welding-society] An evolving metal joining process, welding, suddenly became very necessary to enhance the war effort.
[src:american-welding-society/american-welding-society] To ensure that industry took advantage of this technology, President Woodrow Wilson called upon a Harvard professor, Comfort A.
[src:american-welding-society/american-welding-society] Adams, to chair the Welding Committee of the Emergency Fleet Corp.
[src:american-welding-society/american-welding-society] On March 28, 1919, the American Welding Society was born for that purpose, with Adams serving as its first President.
[src:american-welding-society/american-welding-society] In 1920, the first local Section was organized in Philadelphia, Pennsylvania.
[src:american-welding-society/american-welding-society] By 1922, the American Welding Society had held its first Annual Meeting.
[src:american-welding-society/american-welding-society] Attendees were told of the formation of Sections in eight cities, and also of the establishment of the Journal of the American Welding Society.
[src:american-welding-society/american-welding-society] However, the first meeting also called into discussion the growing financial issues surrounding the depression and proposed solutions to alleviate it.
[src:american-welding-society/american-welding-society] Financial reports delivered at the meeting stated an income for fiscal year ending March 31, 1922, of $12,683.74.
[src:american-welding-society/american-welding-society] The budget for fiscal year 1922-23 was projected at $15,540.
[src:american-welding-society/american-welding-society] It was clear more earnings were needed, so the Society turned to increasing membership numbers of advertising in the Journal as a solution.
[src:american-welding-society/american-welding-society] The American Welding Society's first headquarters were located in New York City, inside the Engineering Societies' Building.
[src:american-welding-society/american-welding-society] For 42 years the organization held all their business in this building, before finally making the move to the United Engineering Center, which was also in New York City.
[src:american-welding-society/american-welding-society] In 1971 the Society once again moved their headquarters – this time to Miami, Florida.
[src:american-welding-society/american-welding-society] The American Welding Society held this location for 30 years before buying its current property in Doral, Florida – only seven miles northwest of the old facility.
[src:american-welding-society/american-welding-society] In August 2012 the American Welding Society moved from their longtime headquarters just outside Coral Gables to their current location in Doral.
[src:american-welding-society/american-welding-society] During the grand opening of the new building, AWS President William Rice said "Our newly renovated five-story building in Doral offers us exactly what we need.
[src:american-welding-society/american-welding-society] The lobby of the headquarters features a bronze sculpture created by sculptor Gregory Johnson and donated to the American Welding Society by President Rice and his wife Cherry.
[src:american-welding-society/american-welding-society] The publication currently known as the *Welding Journal* was born in October 1919 with a different name.
[src:american-welding-society/american-welding-society] The *Journal of the American Welding Society* was its original title – and it had just one issue under this name.
[src:american-welding-society/american-welding-society] In the first publication, American Welding Society President Comfort A.
[src:american-welding-society/american-welding-society] Adams wrote, "The American Bureau of Welding is the authoritative body to establish the facts.
[src:american-welding-society/american-welding-society] To make the most use of the facts, however, requires another sort of machinery and the organization that does this is the American Welding Society.
[src:american-welding-society/american-welding-society] Its function is not to supply the knowledge but to spread it and assist in putting it to practical uses.
[src:american-welding-society/american-welding-society] It is the Society, for instance, which publishes this Journal, which will push matters of importance to welding and which will open out new fields for its use.
[src:american-welding-society/american-welding-society] It holds regular meetings to discuss matters relating to welding, to act upon the recommendation of the Bureau and to initiate further activities.
[src:american-welding-society/american-welding-society] Operating costs were too high for the Journal, and it was not until 1922 that the publication was reborn under its current name thanks to advertising earnings.
[src:american-welding-society/american-welding-society] The society explained the advertising move in their first issue of the newly named *Welding Journal*.
[src:american-welding-society/american-welding-society] "Advertising is also included in this issue, as it was impossible to continue monthly publication without increased revenue.
[src:american-welding-society/american-welding-society] The dues from members of which the National Organization retains half (the other half being returned to local sections) is barely sufficient to pay the ordinary expenses of the Society.
[src:american-welding-society/american-welding-society] Since the move to advertising, the *Welding Journal* has been published continually and continues to be a resource for issues and advancements concerning all types of materials joining, metal fabrication, and construction.
[src:american-welding-society/american-welding-society] It is offered as a benefit to members of the Society, and includes information of the latest products, trends, technology, and events; including articles covering everything from testing and inspection, maintenance and repair, design, training, personal safety, and brazing and soldering.
[src:american-welding-society/american-welding-society] The *Welding Journal* has earned more than 60 editorial and design awards, including multiple Charlie Awards from the Florida Magazine Association (FMA), and Tabbie Awards from the Trade Association Business Publications International (TABPI).
[src:american-welding-society/american-welding-society] The Society now also publishes the *Welding Journal en Español* – a free quarterly publication containing tailored articles written by and for Mexican and Latin American professionals.
[src:american-welding-society/american-welding-society] The *Welding Journal en Español* has a circulation of 10,000 printed copies and 40,000 digital copies.
[src:american-welding-society/american-welding-society] Along with this publication, the *Welding Journal em Português* is a magazine distributed in Brazil to coincide with the Brazil Welding Show that takes place every two years in São Paulo, Brazil.
[src:american-welding-society/american-welding-society] Since the Certified Welding Inspector (CWI) program was introduced in 1976, AWS has certified over 100,000 welding inspectors alone, plus thousands more working professionals across the other certification categories.
[src:american-welding-society/american-welding-society] Certification is accomplished through testing and evaluation of corresponding procedures.
[src:american-welding-society/american-welding-society] The Radiographic Interpretation Certification, for example, includes a detailed general knowledge exam, a test of specific information from the AWS code book on radiographic quality and interpretation, and a practical exam testing the individual's ability to read radiographic films.
[src:american-welding-society/american-welding-society] Most AWS certifications are typically renewed after a period of three years, and are required to satisfy re-certification requirements every nine years.
[src:american-welding-society/american-welding-society] Welders are required to take a qualification test at an AWS Accredited Testing Facility.
[src:american-welding-society/american-welding-society] Welders must mail their qualification test record to AWS with a completed AWS Welder Application in order to have an AWS certification issued.
[src:american-welding-society/american-welding-society] AWS Welders are required to submit a Maintenance of Welder Certification Formto renew their certifications every six months.
[src:american-welding-society/american-welding-society] Endorsements are supplemental inspection credentials available to all AWS Certified Welding Inspectors (CWIs) and Senior Certified Welding Inspectors (SCWIs) to enhance an individual’s credentials.
[src:american-welding-society/american-welding-society] The examinations offered as endorsements to the CWI/SCWI programs are also offered as stand-alone exams to non-CWIs/SCWIs who wish to enhance their educational background.
[src:american-welding-society/american-welding-society] Below are the available endorsement certifications that AWS offers as of 2020.
[src:american-welding-society/american-welding-society] The American Welding Society also certifies the Accredited Test Facilities (ATF) which play an integral part in the operation of their Certification program.
[src:american-welding-society/american-welding-society] The ATF program establishes minimum requirements for test facilities, their personnel and equipment to qualify for accreditation to test and qualify welders.
[src:american-welding-society/american-welding-society] This program is open to all qualified test facilities that may be a part of an independent laboratory, manufacturing plant, educational institution, or other entity.
[src:american-welding-society/american-welding-society] American Welding Society ATFs are listed on the official AWS website and advertised in the American Welding Society's *Welding Journal* magazine.
[src:american-welding-society/american-welding-society] The ATF program requires that a facility implements a quality assurance program that meets the requirements established in the AWS QC4-89, Standard for the Accreditation of Testing Facilities.
[src:american-welding-society/american-welding-society] The requirements include that the facility has a Quality Manual that controls the activities related to the testing of welders in the facility according to AWS QC7, Standard for AWS Certified Welders.
[src:american-welding-society/american-welding-society] The facility must also have a CWI on staff or contracted to perform the welder qualification tests.
[src:american-welding-society/american-welding-society] The American Welding Society explains the benefits of the ATF program on their website by writing "Entrusting welder certification to ATF specialists makes good business sense for contractors and fabricators.
[src:american-welding-society/american-welding-society] Companies are increasingly realizing the shortcomings of self-qualification and switching to AWS Accredited Test Facilities to test and qualify their welders.
[src:american-welding-society/american-welding-society] American Welding Society certifications are not only available to individuals.
[src:american-welding-society/american-welding-society] Companies may also become an official AWS Certified Welding Fabricator (CWF).
[src:american-welding-society/american-welding-society] The American Institute of Steel Construction (AISC) and the American Welding Society have established a reciprocity agreement whereby AISC Certified Fabricators are also eligible to receive certification as an AWS Certified Welding Fabricator.
[src:american-welding-society/american-welding-society] The AISC certification program criteria fully satisfy the AWS Welding Fabricator Certification program requirements.
[src:american-welding-society/american-welding-society] AISC Fabricators that hold current building structures and/or bridge certification may apply to AWS and pay a minimal fee to also attain the AWS Certified Welding Fabricator certification.
[src:american-welding-society/american-welding-society] As of May 2026, the American Welding Society had approximately 63,000 members around the world.
[src:american-welding-society/american-welding-society] AWS publishes codes on multiple aspects of welding and materials joining.
[src:american-welding-society/american-welding-society] The code books are assigned specific letters and numbers for easy reference, and many welders will refer to a specific code letter/number combination when referring to the code book.
[src:american-welding-society/american-welding-society] Different welding methodologies, inspection methods, and metals are published under different codes.
[src:american-welding-society/american-welding-society] For example, AWS B1.11 explains how to visually examine welds; AWS B2.1-1-004 explains welding carbon steel of thickness range of 18 through 10 gauge with semiautomatic metal gas arc welding; and AWS C2.20/C2.20M explains metalized zinc cathodic protection systems.
[src:american-welding-society/american-welding-society] Some codes also describe the standards used by AWS to certify welders, inspectors, and welding educators.
[src:american-welding-society/american-welding-society] All codes are available in hard copy, and in recent years AWS has started to make most codes available online.
[src:american-welding-society/american-welding-society] A very influential AWS code is AWS D1.1, which covers all general requirements for structural welding.
[src:american-welding-society/american-welding-society] This code has been adopted by ANSI as a National Standard in the United States.
[src:american-welding-society/american-welding-society] The American Welding Society extends its reach into local communities through the use of their local sections and student chapters.
[src:american-welding-society/american-welding-society] Section members have the opportunity to network, gain knowledge, and get answers to welding questions from Section members with years of experience.
[src:american-welding-society/american-welding-society] Professional Development Hours may be earned by attending technical meetings, and other planned activities may include educational seminars, plant tours, social events, student programs, community projects and more.
[src:american-welding-society/american-welding-society] The American Welding Society Foundation was founded in 1989 to support research and education in welding and related technologies.
[src:american-welding-society/american-welding-society] It is committed to annually awarding fellowships to deserving graduate students for important research in areas important to the requirements of industry.
[src:american-welding-society/american-welding-society] Accordingly, each year the AWS Foundation administers two $25,000 grants – matched in kind by the participating universities.
[src:american-welding-society/american-welding-society] The award of scholarships to vocational and undergraduate college students is also a high priority.
[src:american-welding-society/american-welding-society] The Image of Welding Awards, presented by the American Welding Society and WEMCO, an association of welding manufacturers, recognize individuals and organizations that have shown exemplary dedication to promoting the image of welding in their communities.
[src:american-welding-society/american-welding-society] Starting in 2015, the awards will now be known as the Excellence in Welding Awards.
[src:american-welding-society/american-welding-society] Recipients of this award will receive a zinc die-cast, 24k gold statue designed by New York firm, Society Awards.
[src:american-welding-society/american-welding-society] The American Welding Society also has several standing committees, or partner organizations, which help promote and advance different facets of the welding industry.
[src:american-welding-society/brazing-p01] During the brazing process, the filler metal flows into the gap between close-fitting parts by capillary action.
[src:american-welding-society/brazing-p01] The filler metal is brought slightly above its melting (liquidus) temperature while protected by a suitable atmosphere, usually a flux.
[src:american-welding-society/brazing-p01] It then flows over the base metal (in a process known as wetting) and is then cooled to join the work pieces together.
[src:american-welding-society/brazing-p01] Brazing differs from welding in that it does not involve melting the work pieces.
[src:american-welding-society/brazing-p01] In welding, the original metal pieces can be fused together without additional filler metal.
[src:american-welding-society/brazing-p01] Brazing differs from soldering through the use of a higher temperature.
[src:american-welding-society/brazing-p01] The principle of joining with filler metal is the same, but solder has a specific composition and lower melting point allowing work on delicate components such as electronics with minimal metallurgic reaction.
[src:american-welding-society/brazing-p01] Brazing joins the same or different metals with considerable strength.
[src:american-welding-society/brazing-p01] Brazing has many advantages over other metal-joining techniques, such as welding.
[src:american-welding-society/brazing-p01] Since brazing does not melt the base metal of the joint, it allows much tighter control over tolerances and produces a clean joint without the need for secondary finishing.
[src:american-welding-society/brazing-p01] Additionally, dissimilar metals and non-metals (i.e. metalized ceramics) can be brazed.
[src:american-welding-society/brazing-p01] In general, brazing also produces less thermal distortion than welding due to the uniform heating of a brazed piece.
[src:american-welding-society/brazing-p01] Complex and multi-part assemblies can be brazed cost-effectively.
[src:american-welding-society/brazing-p01] Welded joints must sometimes be ground flush, a costly secondary operation that brazing does not require because it produces a clean joint.
[src:american-welding-society/brazing-p01] Another advantage is that the brazing can be coated or clad for protective purposes.
[src:american-welding-society/brazing-p01] Finally, brazing is easily adapted to mass production and it is easy to automate because the individual process parameters are less sensitive to variation.
[src:american-welding-society/brazing-p01] One of the main disadvantages is the lack of joint strength as compared to a welded joint due to the softer filler metals used.
[src:american-welding-society/brazing-p01] The strength of the brazed joint is likely to be less than that of the base metal(s) but greater than the filler metal.
[src:american-welding-society/brazing-p01] Another disadvantage is that brazed joints can be damaged under high service temperatures.
[src:american-welding-society/brazing-p01] Brazed joints require a high degree of base-metal cleanliness when done in an industrial setting.
[src:american-welding-society/brazing-p01] Some brazing applications require the use of adequate fluxing agents to control cleanliness.
[src:american-welding-society/brazing-p01] The joint color is often different from that of the base metal, creating an aesthetic disadvantage.
[src:american-welding-society/brazing-p01] High-quality brazed joints require that parts be closely fitted with base metal surfaces exceptionally clean and free of oxides.
[src:american-welding-society/brazing-p01] In most cases, joint clearances of 0.03 to 0.08 mm (0.0012 to 0.0031 in) are recommended for the best capillary action and joint strength; in some brazing operations, however, it is not uncommon to have joint clearances around 0.6 mm (0.024 in).
[src:american-welding-society/brazing-p01] Cleanliness of the brazing surfaces is also important, as any contamination can cause poor wetting (flow).
[src:american-welding-society/brazing-p01] The two main methods for cleaning parts, prior to brazing, are chemical cleaning and abrasive or mechanical cleaning.
[src:american-welding-society/brazing-p01] In the case of mechanical cleaning it is important to maintain the proper surface roughness, as wetting on a rough surface occurs much more readily than on a smooth surface of the same geometry.
[src:american-welding-society/brazing-p01] Another consideration is the effect of temperature and time on the quality of brazed joints.
[src:american-welding-society/brazing-p01] As the temperature of the braze alloy is increased, the alloying and wetting action of the filler metal increases as well.
[src:american-welding-society/brazing-p01] In general, the brazing temperature selected must be above the melting point of the filler metal.
[src:american-welding-society/brazing-p01] However, several factors influence the joint designer's temperature selection.
[src:american-welding-society/brazing-p01] In some cases, a worker may select a higher temperature to accommodate other factors in the design (e.g., to allow use of a different filler metal, or to control metallurgical effects, or to sufficiently remove surface contamination).
[src:american-welding-society/brazing-p01] The effect of time on the brazed joint primarily affects the extent to which these effects are present.
[src:american-welding-society/brazing-p01] In general, however, most production processes are selected to minimize brazing time and associated costs.
[src:american-welding-society/brazing-p01] This is not always the case, however, since in some non-production settings, time and cost are secondary to other joint attributes (e.g., strength, appearance).
[src:american-welding-society/brazing-p01] There are many heating methods available to accomplish brazing operations.
[src:american-welding-society/brazing-p01] The most important factor in choosing a heating method is achieving efficient transfer of heat throughout the joint and doing so within the heat capacity of the individual base metals used.
[src:american-welding-society/brazing-p01] The geometry of the braze joint is also a crucial factor to consider, as is the rate and volume of production required.
[src:american-welding-society/brazing-p01] The easiest way to categorize brazing methods is to group them by heating method.
[src:american-welding-society/brazing-p01] These heating methods are classified through localised and diffuse heating techniques and offer advantages based on their different applications.
[src:american-welding-society/brazing-p01] Torch brazing is by far the most common method of mechanized brazing in use.
[src:american-welding-society/brazing-p01] It is best used in small production volumes or in specialized operations, and in some countries, it accounts for a majority of the brazing taking place.
[src:american-welding-society/brazing-p01] There are three main categories of torch brazing in use: manual, machine, and automatic torch brazing.
[src:american-welding-society/brazing-p01] Furnace brazing is a semi-automatic process used widely in industrial brazing operations due to its adaptability to mass production and use of unskilled labor.
[src:american-welding-society/brazing-p01] There are many advantages of furnace brazing over other heating methods that make it ideal for mass production.
[src:american-welding-society/brazing-p01] One main advantage is the ease with which it can produce large numbers of small parts that are easily jigged or self-locating.
[src:american-welding-society/brazing-p01] The process also offers the benefits of a controlled heat cycle (allowing use of parts that might distort under localized heating) and no need for post braze cleaning.
[src:american-welding-society/brazing-p01] Common atmospheres used include: inert, reducing or vacuum atmospheres all of which protect the part from oxidation.
[src:american-welding-society/brazing-p01] Some other advantages include: low unit cost when used in mass production, close temperature control, and the ability to braze multiple joints at once.
[src:american-welding-society/brazing-p01] Furnaces are typically heated using either electric, gas or oil depending on the type of furnace and application.
[src:american-welding-society/brazing-p01] However, some of the disadvantages of this method include: high capital equipment cost, more difficult design considerations and high power consumption.
[src:american-welding-society/brazing-p01] There are four main types of furnaces used in brazing operations: batch type; continuous; retort with controlled atmosphere; and vacuum.
[src:american-welding-society/brazing-p01] A *batch* type furnace has relatively low initial equipment costs, and can heat each part load separately.
[src:american-welding-society/brazing-p01] It can be turned on and off at will, which reduces operating expenses when it's not in use.
[src:american-welding-society/brazing-p01] These furnaces are suited to medium to large volume production, and offer a large degree of flexibility in type of parts that can be brazed.
[src:american-welding-society/brazing-p01] Either controlled atmospheres or flux can be used to control oxidation and cleanliness of parts.
[src:american-welding-society/brazing-p01] Silver brazing, sometimes known as hard soldering, is brazing using a silver alloy based filler.
[src:american-welding-society/brazing-p01] These silver alloys consist of many different percentages of silver and other metals, such as copper, zinc and cadmium.
[src:american-welding-society/brazing-p01] Brazing is widely used in the tool industry to fasten "hard metal" (carbide, ceramics, cermet, and similar) tips to tools such as saw blades.
[src:american-welding-society/brazing-p01] "Pretinning" is often done: the braze alloy is melted onto the hard metal tip, which is placed next to the steel and remelted.
[src:american-welding-society/brazing-p01] Pretinning gets around the problem that hard metals are difficult to wet.
[src:american-welding-society/brazing-p01] Brazed hard metal joints are typically two to seven mils thick.
[src:american-welding-society/brazing-p01] The braze alloy joins the materials and compensates for the difference in their expansion rates.
[src:american-welding-society/brazing-p01] It also provides a cushion between the hard carbide tip and the hard steel, which softens impact and prevents tip loss and damage—much as a vehicle's suspension helps prevent damage to the tires and the vehicle.
[src:american-welding-society/brazing-p01] Finally, the braze alloy joins the other two materials to create a composite structure, much as layers of wood and glue create plywood.
[src:american-welding-society/brazing-p01] The standard for braze joint strength in many industries is a joint that is stronger than either base material, so that when under stress, one or other of the base materials fails before the joint.
[src:american-welding-society/brazing-p01] Silver brazing may cause defects in certain alloys, e.g. stress-induced inter-granular cracking in copper-nickel.
[src:american-welding-society/brazing-p01] One special silver brazing method is called *pinbrazing* or *pin brazing*.
[src:american-welding-society/brazing-p01] It has been developed especially for connecting cables to railway track or for cathodic protection installations.
[src:american-welding-society/brazing-p01] The method uses a silver- and flux-containing brazing pin, which is melted in the eye of a cable lug.
[src:american-welding-society/brazing-p01] The equipment is normally powered from batteries.
[src:american-welding-society/brazing-p01] Braze welding has many advantages over fusion welding.
[src:american-welding-society/brazing-p01] It allows the joining of dissimilar metals, minimization of heat distortion, and can reduce the need for extensive pre-heating.
[src:american-welding-society/brazing-p01] Additionally, since the metals joined are not melted in the process, the components retain their original shape; edges and contours are not eroded or changed by the formation of a fillet.
[src:american-welding-society/brazing-p01] Another effect of braze welding is the elimination of stored-up stresses that are often present in fusion welding.
[src:american-welding-society/brazing-p01] This is extremely important in the repair of large castings.
[src:american-welding-society/brazing-p01] The disadvantages are the loss of strength when subjected to high temperatures and the inability to withstand high stresses.
[src:american-welding-society/brazing-p01] Carbide, cermet and ceramic tips are plated and then joined to steel to make tipped band saws.
[src:american-welding-society/brazing-p01] The "welding" of cast iron is usually a brazing operation, with a filler rod made chiefly of nickel being used although true welding with cast iron rods is also available.
[src:american-welding-society/brazing-p01] Ductile cast iron pipe may be also "cadwelded," a process that connects joints by means of a small copper wire fused into the iron when previously ground down to the bare metal, parallel to the iron joints being formed as per hub pipe with neoprene gasket seals.
[src:american-welding-society/brazing-p01] The purpose behind this operation is to use electricity along the copper for keeping underground pipes warm in cold climates.
[src:american-welding-society/brazing-p01] Vacuum brazing is a material joining technique that offers significant advantages: extremely clean, superior, flux-free braze joints of high integrity and strength.
[src:american-welding-society/brazing-p01] The process can be expensive because it must be performed inside a vacuum chamber vessel.
[src:american-welding-society/brazing-p01] Temperature uniformity is maintained on the work piece when heating in a vacuum, greatly reducing residual stresses due to slow heating and cooling cycles.
[src:american-welding-society/brazing-p01] This, in turn, can significantly improve the thermal and mechanical properties of the material, thus providing unique heat treatment capabilities.
[src:american-welding-society/brazing-p01] One such capability is heat-treating or age-hardening the workpiece while performing a metal-joining process, all in a single furnace thermal cycle.
[src:american-welding-society/brazing-p01] Products that are most commonly vacuum-brazed include aluminum cold plates, plate-fin heat exchangers, and flat tube heat exchangers.
[src:american-welding-society/brazing-p01] Vacuum brazing is often conducted in a furnace; this means that several joints can be made at once because the whole workpiece reaches the brazing temperature.
[src:american-welding-society/brazing-p01] The heat is transferred using radiation, as many other methods cannot be used in a vacuum.
[src:american-welding-society/brazing-p01] Dip brazing is especially suited for brazing aluminium because air is excluded, thus preventing the formation of oxides.
[src:american-welding-society/brazing-p01] The parts to be joined are fixtured and the brazing compound applied to the mating surfaces, typically in slurry form.
[src:american-welding-society/brazing-p01] Then the assemblies are dipped into a bath of molten salt (typically NaCl, KCl and other compounds), which functions as both heat transfer medium and flux.
[src:american-welding-society/brazing-p01] Many dip brazed parts are used in heat transfer applications for the aerospace industry.
[src:american-welding-society/brazing-p01] A variety of alloys are used as filler metals for brazing depending on the intended use or application method.
[src:american-welding-society/brazing-p01] In general, braze alloys are composed of three or more metals to form an alloy with the desired properties.
[src:american-welding-society/brazing-p01] The filler metal for a particular application is chosen based on its ability to: wet the base metals, withstand the service conditions required, and melt at a lower temperature than the base metals or at a very specific temperature.
[src:american-welding-society/brazing-p01] Braze alloy is generally available as rod, ribbon, powder, paste, cream, wire and preforms (such as stamped washers).
[src:american-welding-society/brazing-p01] Depending on the application, the filler material can be pre-placed at the desired location or applied during the heating cycle.
[src:american-welding-society/brazing-p01] For manual brazing, wire and rod forms are generally used as they are the easiest to apply while heating.
[src:american-welding-society/brazing-p01] In the case of furnace brazing, the alloy is usually placed beforehand since the process is usually highly automated.
[src:american-welding-society/brazing-p01] Some brazes come in the form of *trifoils*, laminated foils of a carrier metal clad with a layer of braze at each side.
[src:american-welding-society/brazing-p01] Brazing alloys form several distinct groups; the alloys in the same group have similar properties and uses.
[src:american-welding-society/brazing-p01] Often noble metals – silver, gold, palladium.
[src:american-welding-society/brazing-p01] Eutectic alloy used for furnace brazing.
[src:american-welding-society/brazing-p01] Copper-rich alloys prone to stress cracking by ammonia.
[src:american-welding-society/brazing-p01] The color matches silver, and it is resistant to ammonia-containing silver-cleaning fluids.
[src:american-welding-society/brazing-p01] General purpose, used for joining steel and cast iron.
[src:american-welding-society/brazing-p01] Corrosion resistance usually inadequate for copper, silicon bronze, copper-nickel, and stainless steel.
[src:american-welding-society/brazing-p01] High vapor pressure due to volatile zinc, unsuitable for furnace brazing.
[src:american-welding-society/brazing-p01] Lower melting point than Ag-Cu for same Ag content.
[src:american-welding-society/brazing-p01] At above 40% Zn the ductility and strength drop, so only lower-zinc alloys of this type are used.
[src:american-welding-society/brazing-p01] At above 25% zinc less ductile copper-zinc and silver-zinc phases appear.
[src:american-welding-society/brazing-p01] Silver content above 85% yields reduced strength, high liquidus and high cost.
[src:american-welding-society/brazing-p01] Silver-rich brazes (above 67.5% Ag) are hallmarkable and used in jewellery; alloys with lower silver content are used for engineering purposes.
[src:american-welding-society/brazing-p01] Alloys with copper-zinc ratio of about 60:40 contain the same phases as brass and match its color; they are used for joining brass.
[src:american-welding-society/brazing-p01] Small amount of nickel improves strength and corrosion resistance and promotes wetting of carbides.
[src:american-welding-society/brazing-p01] Addition of manganese together with nickel increases fracture toughness.
[src:american-welding-society/brazing-p01] alloys with improved fluidity and wetting and lower melting point; however cadmium is toxic.
[src:american-welding-society/brazing-p01] Addition of tin can play mostly the same role.
[src:american-welding-society/brazing-p01] Widely used for copper and copper alloys.
[src:american-welding-society/brazing-p01] Can be also used with silver, tungsten, and molybdenum.
[src:american-welding-society/brazing-p01] More ductile, better electrical conductivity.
[src:american-welding-society/brazing-p01] Readily wet many metals, including refractory ones.
[src:american-welding-society/brazing-p01] Alloys with 40–90% of gold harden on cooling but stay ductile.
[src:american-welding-society/brazing-p01] Silver lowers melting point but worsens corrosion resistance.
[src:american-welding-society/brazing-p01] To maintain corrosion resistance, gold must be kept above 60%.
[src:american-welding-society/brazing-p01] High-temperature strength and corrosion resistance can be improved by further alloying, e.g., with chromium, palladium, manganese, and molybdenum.
[src:american-welding-society/brazing-p01] Wider melting range than Au-Cu alloys but better corrosion resistance and improved wetting.
[src:american-welding-society/brazing-p01] Frequently alloyed with other metals to reduce proportion of gold while maintaining properties.
[src:american-welding-society/brazing-p01] Copper may be added to lower gold proportion, chromium to compensate for loss of corrosion resistance, and boron for improving wetting impaired by the chromium.
[src:american-welding-society/brazing-p01] Generally no more than 35% Ni is used, as higher Ni/Au ratios have too wide melting range.
[src:american-welding-society/brazing-p01] Improved corrosion resistance over Au-Cu and Au-Ni alloys.
[src:american-welding-society/brazing-p01] Used for joining superalloys and refractory metals for high-temperature applications, e.g. jet engines.
[src:american-welding-society/brazing-p01] May be substituted for by cobalt-based brazes.
[src:american-welding-society/brazing-p01] Good high-temperature performance, high corrosion resistance (less than gold), high strength (more than gold). usually alloyed with nickel, copper, or silver.
[src:american-welding-society/brazing-p01] Forms solid solutions with most metals, does not form brittle intermetallics.
[src:american-welding-society/brazing-p01] Nickel alloys, even more numerous than silver alloys.
[src:american-welding-society/brazing-p01] Good high-temperature performance, good corrosion resistance in moderately aggressive environments.
[src:american-welding-society/brazing-p01] Often used for stainless steels and heat-resistant alloys.
[src:american-welding-society/brazing-p01] Embrittled with sulfur and some lower-melting point metals, e.g. zinc.
[src:american-welding-society/brazing-p01] Boron, phosphorus, silicon and carbon lower melting point and rapidly diffuse to base metals.
[src:american-welding-society/brazing-p01] This allows diffusion brazing, and lets the joint be used above the brazing temperature.
[src:american-welding-society/brazing-p01] Borides and phosphides form brittle phases.
[src:american-welding-society/brazing-p01] Amorphous preforms can be made by rapid solidification.
[src:american-welding-society/brazing-p01] Good high-temperature corrosion resistance, possible alternative to Au-Pd brazes.
[src:american-welding-society/brazing-p01] Low workability at low temperatures, preforms prepared by rapid solidification.
[src:american-welding-society/brazing-p01] Containing active metals, e.g., titanium or vanadium.
[src:american-welding-society/brazing-p01] Used for brazing non-metallic materials, e.g.
[src:american-welding-society/brazing-p01] Some additives and impurities act at very low levels.
[src:american-welding-society/brazing-p01] Both positive and negative effects can be observed.
[src:american-welding-society/brazing-p01] Strontium at levels of 0.01% refines grain structure of aluminum.
[src:american-welding-society/brazing-p01] Beryllium and bismuth at similar levels help disrupt the passivation layer of aluminum oxide and promote wetting.
[src:american-welding-society/brazing-p01] Carbon at 0.1% impairs corrosion resistance of nickel alloys.
[src:american-welding-society/brazing-p01] Aluminum can embrittle mild steel at 0.001%, phosphorus at 0.01%.
[src:american-welding-society/brazing-p01] In some cases, especially for vacuum brazing, high-purity metals and alloys are used.
[src:american-welding-society/brazing-p01] 99.99% and 99.999% purity levels are available commercially.
[src:american-welding-society/brazing-p01] Care must be taken to not introduce deleterious impurities from joint contamination or by dissolution of the base metals during brazing.
[src:american-welding-society/brazing-p01] Alloys with larger span of solidus/liquidus temperatures tend to melt through a "mushy" state, during which the alloy is a mixture of solid and liquid material.
[src:american-welding-society/brazing-p01] Some alloys show tendency to **liquation**, separation of the liquid from the solid portion; for these the heating through the melting range must be sufficiently fast to avoid this effect.
[src:american-welding-society/brazing-p01] Some alloys show extended plastic range, when only a small portion of the alloy is liquid and most of the material melts at the upper temperature range; these are suitable for bridging large gaps and for forming fillets.
[src:american-welding-society/brazing-p01] Highly fluid alloys are suitable for penetrating deep into narrow gaps and for brazing tight joints with narrow tolerances but are not suitable for filling larger gaps.
[src:american-welding-society/brazing-p01] Alloys with wider melting range are less sensitive to non-uniform clearances.
[src:american-welding-society/brazing-p01] When the brazing temperature is suitably high, brazing and heat treatment can be done in a single operation simultaneously.
[src:american-welding-society/brazing-p01] Eutectic alloys melt at single temperature, without mushy region.
[src:american-welding-society/brazing-p01] Eutectic alloys have superior spreading; non-eutectics in the mushy region have high viscosity and at the same time attack the base metal, with correspondingly lower spreading force.
[src:american-welding-society/brazing-p01] Fine grain size gives eutectics both increased strength and increased ductility.
[src:american-welding-society/brazing-p01] Highly accurate melting temperature lets joining process be performed only slightly above the alloy's melting point.
[src:american-welding-society/brazing-p01] On solidifying, there is no mushy state where the alloy appears solid but is not yet; the chance of disturbing the joint by manipulation in such state is reduced (assuming the alloy did not significantly change its properties by dissolving the base metal).
[src:american-welding-society/brazing-p01] Eutectic behavior is especially beneficial for solders.
[src:american-welding-society/brazing-p01] Metals with fine grain structure before melting provide superior wetting to metals with large grains.
[src:american-welding-society/brazing-p01] Alloying additives (e.g. strontium to aluminum) can be added to refine grain structure, and the preforms or foils can be prepared by rapid quenching.
[src:american-welding-society/brazing-p01] Very rapid quenching may provide amorphous metal structure, which possess further advantages.
[src:american-welding-society/brazing-p01] For successful wetting, the base metal must be at least partially soluble in at least one component of the brazing alloy.
[src:american-welding-society/brazing-p01] The molten alloy therefore tends to attack the base metal and dissolve it, slightly changing its composition in the process.
[src:american-welding-society/brazing-p01] The composition change is reflected in the change of the alloy's melting point and the corresponding change of fluidity.
[src:american-welding-society/brazing-p01] For example, some alloys dissolve both silver and copper; dissolved silver lowers their melting point and increases fluidity, copper has the opposite effect.
[src:american-welding-society/brazing-p01] The melting point change can be exploited.
[src:american-welding-society/brazing-p01] As the remelt temperature can be increased by enriching the alloy with dissolved base metal, step brazing using the same braze can be possible.
[src:american-welding-society/brazing-p01] Alloys that do not significantly attack the base metals are more suitable for brazing thin sections.
[src:american-welding-society/brazing-p01] Nonhomogenous microstructure of the braze may cause non-uniform melting and localized erosions of the base metal.
[src:american-welding-society/brazing-p01] Wetting of base metals can be improved by adding a suitable metal to the alloy.
[src:american-welding-society/brazing-p01] Tin facilitates wetting of iron, nickel, and many other alloys.
[src:american-welding-society/brazing-p01] Copper wets ferrous metals that silver does not attack, copper-silver alloys can therefore braze steels silver alone won't wet.
[src:american-welding-society/brazing-p01] Zinc improves wetting of ferrous metals, indium as well.
[src:american-welding-society/brazing-p01] Aluminum improves wetting of aluminum alloys.
[src:american-welding-society/brazing-p01] For wetting of ceramics, reactive metals capable of forming chemical compounds with the ceramic (e.g. titanium, vanadium, zirconium...) can be added to the braze.
[src:american-welding-society/brazing-p01] Dissolution of base metals can cause detrimental changes in the brazing alloy.
[src:american-welding-society/brazing-p01] For example, aluminum dissolved from aluminum bronzes can embrittle the braze; addition of nickel to the braze can offset this.
[src:american-welding-society/brazing-p01] The effect works both ways; there can be detrimental interactions between the braze alloy and the base metal.
[src:american-welding-society/brazing-p01] Presence of phosphorus in the braze alloy leads to formation of brittle phosphides of iron and nickel, phosphorus-containing alloys are therefore unsuitable for brazing nickel and ferrous alloys.
[src:american-welding-society/brazing-p01] Boron tends to diffuse into the base metals, especially along the grain boundaries, and may form brittle borides.
[src:american-welding-society/brazing-p01] Carbon can negatively influence some steels.
[src:american-welding-society/brazing-p01] Care must be taken to avoid galvanic corrosion between the braze and the base metal, and especially between dissimilar base metals being brazed together.
[src:american-welding-society/brazing-p01] Formation of brittle intermetallic compounds on the alloy interface can cause joint failure.
[src:american-welding-society/brazing-p01] This is discussed more in-depth with solders.
[src:american-welding-society/brazing-p01] The potentially detrimental phases may be distributed evenly through the volume of the alloy, or be concentrated on the braze-base interface.
[src:american-welding-society/brazing-p01] A thick layer of interfacial intermetallics is usually considered detrimental due to its commonly low fracture toughness and other sub-par mechanical properties.
[src:american-welding-society/brazing-p01] In some situations, e.g. die attaching, it however does not matter much as silicon chips are not typically subjected to mechanical abuse.
[src:american-welding-society/brazing-p01] On wetting, brazes may liberate elements from the base metal.
[src:american-welding-society/brazing-p01] For example, aluminum-silicon braze wets silicon nitride, dissociates the surface so it can react with silicon, and liberates nitrogen, which may create voids along the joint interface and lower its strength.
[src:american-welding-society/brazing-p01] Titanium-containing nickel-gold braze wets silicon nitride and reacts with its surface, forming titanium nitride and liberating silicon; silicon then forms brittle nickel silicides and eutectic gold-silicon phase; the resulting joint is weak and melts at much lower temperature than may be expected.
[src:american-welding-society/brazing-p01] Metals may diffuse from one base alloy to the other one, causing embrittlement or corrosion.
[src:american-welding-society/brazing-p01] An example is diffusion of aluminum from aluminum bronze to a ferrous alloy when joining these.
[src:american-welding-society/brazing-p01] A diffusion barrier, e.g. a copper layer (e.g. in a trimet strip), can be used.
[src:american-welding-society/brazing-p01] A sacrificial layer of a noble metal can be used on the base metal as an oxygen barrier, preventing formation of oxides and facilitating fluxless brazing.
[src:american-welding-society/brazing-p01] During brazing, the noble metal layer dissolves in the filler metal.
[src:american-welding-society/brazing-p01] Copper or nickel plating of stainless steels performs the same function.
[src:american-welding-society/brazing-p01] In brazing copper, a reducing atmosphere (or even a reducing flame) may react with the oxygen residues in the metal, which are present as cuprous oxide inclusions, and cause hydrogen embrittlement.
[src:american-welding-society/brazing-p01] The hydrogen present in the flame or atmosphere at high temperature reacts with the oxide, yielding metallic copper and water vapour, steam.
[src:american-welding-society/brazing-p01] The steam bubbles exert high pressure in the metal structure, leading to cracks and joint porosity.
[src:american-welding-society/brazing-p01] Oxygen-free copper is not sensitive to this effect, however the most readily available grades, e.g. electrolytic copper or high-conductivity copper, are.
[src:american-welding-society/brazing-p01] The embrittled joint may then fail catastrophically without any previous sign of deformation or deterioration.
[src:american-welding-society/brazing-p01] Unless brazing operations are contained within an inert or reducing atmosphere environment (i.e.
[src:american-welding-society/brazing-p01] Nitrogen), a flux such as borax is required to prevent oxides from forming while the metal is heated.
[src:american-welding-society/brazing-p01] The flux also serves the purpose of cleaning any contamination left on the brazing surfaces.
[src:american-welding-society/brazing-p01] Flux can be applied in any number of forms including flux paste, liquid, powder or pre-made brazing pastes that combine flux with filler metal powder.
[src:american-welding-society/brazing-p01] Flux can also be applied using brazing rods with a coating of flux, or a flux core.
[src:american-welding-society/brazing-p01] In either case, the flux flows into the joint when applied to the heated joint and is displaced by the molten filler metal entering the joint.
[src:american-welding-society/brazing-p01] Excess flux should be removed when the cycle is completed because flux left in the joint can lead to corrosion, impede joint inspection, and prevent further surface finishing operations.
[src:american-welding-society/brazing-p01] Phosphorus-containing brazing alloys can be self-fluxing when joining copper to copper.
[src:american-welding-society/brazing-p01] Fluxes are generally selected based on their performance on particular base metals.
[src:american-welding-society/brazing-p01] To be effective, the flux must be chemically compatible with both the base metal and the filler metal being used.
[src:american-welding-society/brazing-p01] Self-fluxing phosphorus filler alloys produce brittle phosphides if used on iron or nickel.
[src:american-welding-society/brazing-p01] As a general rule, longer brazing cycles should use less active fluxes than short brazing operations.
[src:american-welding-society/brazing-p02] As brazing work requires high temperatures, oxidation of the metal surface occurs in an oxygen-containing atmosphere.
[src:american-welding-society/brazing-p02] This may necessitate the use of an atmospheric environment other than air.
[src:american-welding-society/brazing-p02] Acid cleaning bath or mechanical cleaning can be used to remove the oxidation after work.
[src:american-welding-society/brazing-p02] Flux counteracts the oxidation, but may weaken the joint.
[src:american-welding-society/brazing-p02] Low hydrogen, AWS type 1, "exothermic generated atmospheres".
[src:american-welding-society/brazing-p02] For silver, copper-phosphorus and copper-zinc filler metals.
[src:american-welding-society/brazing-p02] , AWS type 2, "endothermic generated atmospheres.
[src:american-welding-society/brazing-p02] For copper, silver, copper-phosphorus and copper-zinc filler metals.
[src:american-welding-society/brazing-p02] Dried, AWS type 3, "endothermic generated atmospheres.
[src:american-welding-society/brazing-p02] Dissociated ammonia (75% hydrogen, 25% nitrogen) can be used for many types of brazing and annealing.
[src:american-welding-society/brazing-p02] For copper, silver, nickel, copper-phosphorus and copper-zinc filler metals.
[src:american-welding-society/brazing-p02] Strong deoxidizer, highly thermally conductive.
[src:american-welding-society/brazing-p02] Can be used for copper brazing and annealing steel.
[src:american-welding-society/brazing-p02] and chromium alloys, cobalt alloys, tungsten alloys, and carbides.
[src:american-welding-society/brazing-p02] Can be mixed with atmospheres AWS 1–5 to replace flux.
[src:american-welding-society/brazing-p02] Non-oxidizing, more expensive than nitrogen.
[src:american-welding-society/brazing-p02] Parts must be very clean, gas must be pure.
[src:american-welding-society/brazing-p02] chromium alloys, titanium, zirconium, hafnium.
[src:american-welding-society/brazing-p02] Unsuitable (or requires special care) for metals with high vapor pressure, e.g. silver, zinc, phosphorus, cadmium, and manganese.
[src:american-welding-society/brazing-p02] Used for highest-quality joints, for e.g.
[src:american-welding-society/brazing-p02] A brazing preform is a high quality, precision metal stamping used for a variety of joining applications in manufacturing electronic devices and systems.
[src:american-welding-society/brazing-p02] Typical brazing preform uses include attaching electronic circuitry, packaging electronic devices, providing good thermal and electrical conductivity, and providing an interface for electronic connections.
[src:american-welding-society/brazing-p02] Square, rectangular and disc shaped brazing preforms are commonly used to attach electronic components containing silicon dies to a substrate such as a printed circuit board.
[src:american-welding-society/brazing-p02] Rectangular frame shaped preforms are often required for the construction of electronic packages while washer shaped brazing preforms are typically utilized to attach lead wires and hermetic feed-throughs to electronic circuits and packages.
[src:american-welding-society/brazing-p02] Some preforms are also used in diodes, rectifiers, optoelectronic devices and components packaging.
[src:american-welding-society/brazing-p02] Brazing may entail exposure to hazardous chemical fumes.
[src:american-welding-society/brazing-p02] The National Institute for Occupational Safety and Health in the United States recommends that exposure to these fumes is controlled to levels below the allowed exposure limit.
[src:american-welding-society/carbon-steel] The addition of significant amounts of other metals, such as nickel, chromium, vanadium, molybdenum, changes the materials definition from carbon steel to alloy steel.
[src:american-welding-society/carbon-steel] As the carbon content percentage rises, steel has the ability to become harder and stronger through heat treating; however, it becomes less ductile.
[src:american-welding-society/carbon-steel] Regardless of the heat treatment, a higher carbon content reduces weldability.
[src:american-welding-society/carbon-steel] In carbon steels, the higher carbon content lowers the melting point.
[src:american-welding-society/carbon-steel] High-carbon steel has many uses, primarily applications where medium strength and low material cost are factors, including: high strength steel wires, springs, bolts, garden and agricultural tools, wood chisels and axes.
[src:american-welding-society/carbon-steel] Carbon steel is often divided into two main categories: low-carbon steel and high-carbon steel.
[src:american-welding-society/carbon-steel] It may also contain other elements, such as manganese, phosphorus, sulfur, and silicon, which can affect its properties.
[src:american-welding-society/carbon-steel] Low carbon steel can be easily machined and welded, making it versatile and suitable for various applications which require reasonable strength and low material cost such as car body panels, footbridges, hand rails, garden furniture/park benches, nails, gates etc .
[src:american-welding-society/carbon-steel] Higher carbon is less easily machined and is much less suitable for welding, but can be heat treated to improve its strength, hardness, and durability.
[src:american-welding-society/carbon-steel] Carbon steel is susceptible to rust and corrosion, especially in environments with high moisture levels and/or salt.
[src:american-welding-society/carbon-steel] It can be shielded from corrosion by coating it with paint, varnish, or other protective material.
[src:american-welding-society/carbon-steel] Alternatively, it can be made from a stainless steel alloy that contains chromium, which provides excellent corrosion resistance.
[src:american-welding-society/carbon-steel] Carbon steel can be alloyed with other elements to improve its properties, such as by adding chromium and/or nickel to improve its resistance to corrosion and oxidation or adding molybdenum to improve its strength and toughness at high temperatures.
[src:american-welding-society/carbon-steel] Mild steel contains approximately 0.05–0.30% carbon making it malleable and ductile.
[src:american-welding-society/carbon-steel] Mild steel has a relatively low tensile strength, but it is cheap and easy to form.
[src:american-welding-society/carbon-steel] Surface hardness can be increased with carburization.
[src:american-welding-society/carbon-steel] The density of mild steel is approximately 7.85 g/cm3 (7,850 kg/m3; 0.284 lb/cu in) and the Young's modulus is 200 GPa (29×10^6 psi).
[src:american-welding-society/carbon-steel] Low-carbon steels display *yield-point runout* where the material has two yield points.
[src:american-welding-society/carbon-steel] The first yield point (or upper yield point) is higher than the second and the yield drops dramatically after the upper yield point.
[src:american-welding-society/carbon-steel] If a low-carbon steel is only stressed to some point between the upper and lower yield point then the surface develops Lüder bands.
[src:american-welding-society/carbon-steel] Low-carbon steels contain less carbon than other steels and are easier to cold-form, making them easier to handle.
[src:american-welding-society/carbon-steel] Typical applications of low carbon steel are car parts, pipes, construction, and food cans.
[src:american-welding-society/carbon-steel] Steels which have a carbon content above ~0.3% can have their hardness and tensile strength modified by heat treatment.
[src:american-welding-society/carbon-steel] Heating to approximately 850c followed by rapid cooling/quenching in water or oil increases hardness and tensile strength, but it also reduces maleability, increases brittleness and make fractures and breakages much more likely.
[src:american-welding-society/carbon-steel] To reduce these brittleness problems whilst still achieving high levels of hardness and tensile strength, low or medium carbon steels are alloyed with other metals.
[src:american-welding-society/carbon-steel] These alloy steels also require specific heat treatment to achieve the required mechanical properties, and the tensile strength/hardness trade off vs malleability remains, but to a much lesser extent compared to low alloy carbon steel.
[src:american-welding-society/carbon-steel] Alloying ingredients include chromium, molybdenum, silicon, manganese, nickel, and vanadium.
[src:american-welding-society/carbon-steel] The relative scarcity and high cost of these metals compared to iron is primarily what restricts their use.
[src:american-welding-society/carbon-steel] Carbon steels which can successfully undergo heat-treatment have a carbon content in the range of 0.30–1.70% by weight.
[src:american-welding-society/carbon-steel] Trace impurities of various other elements can significantly affect the quality of the resulting steel.
[src:american-welding-society/carbon-steel] Trace amounts of sulfur in particular make the steel red-short, that is, brittle and crumbly at high working temperatures.
[src:american-welding-society/carbon-steel] Manganese is often added to improve the hardenability of low-carbon steels.
[src:american-welding-society/carbon-steel] These additions turn the material into a low-alloy steel by some definitions, but AISI's definition of carbon steel allows up to 1.65% manganese by weight.
[src:american-welding-society/carbon-steel] There are two types of higher carbon steels which are high carbon steel and the ultra high carbon steel.
[src:american-welding-society/carbon-steel] The reason for the limited use of high carbon steel is that it has extremely poor ductility and weldability and has a higher cost of production.
[src:american-welding-society/carbon-steel] The applications best suited for the high carbon steels is its use in the spring industry, farm industry, and in the production of wide range of high-strength wires.
[src:american-welding-society/carbon-steel] Different classifications of non-alloy steel exist.
[src:american-welding-society/carbon-steel] The purpose of heat treating carbon steel is to change the mechanical properties of steel, usually ductility, hardness, yield strength, or impact resistance.
[src:american-welding-society/carbon-steel] Note that the electrical and thermal conductivity are only slightly altered.
[src:american-welding-society/carbon-steel] As with most strengthening techniques for steel, Young's modulus (elasticity) is unaffected.
[src:american-welding-society/carbon-steel] All treatments of steel trade ductility for increased strength and vice versa.
[src:american-welding-society/carbon-steel] Iron has a higher solubility for carbon in the austenite phase; therefore all heat treatments, except spheroidizing and process annealing, start by heating the steel to a temperature at which the austenitic phase can exist.
[src:american-welding-society/carbon-steel] The steel is then quenched (heat drawn out) at a moderate to low rate allowing carbon to diffuse out of the austenite forming iron-carbide (cementite) and leaving ferrite, or at a high rate, trapping the carbon within the iron thus forming martensite.
[src:american-welding-society/carbon-steel] The rate at which the steel is cooled through the eutectoid temperature (about 727 °C or 1,341 °F) affects the rate at which carbon diffuses out of austenite and forms cementite.
[src:american-welding-society/carbon-steel] Generally speaking, cooling swiftly will leave iron carbide finely dispersed and produce a fine grained pearlite and cooling slowly will give a coarser pearlite.
[src:american-welding-society/carbon-steel] Cooling a hypoeutectoid steel (less than 0.77 wt% C) results in a lamellar-pearlitic structure of iron carbide layers with α-ferrite (nearly pure iron) between.
[src:american-welding-society/carbon-steel] If it is hypereutectoid steel (more than 0.77 wt% C) then the structure is full pearlite with small grains (larger than the pearlite lamella) of cementite formed on the grain boundaries.
[src:american-welding-society/carbon-steel] A eutectoid steel (0.77% carbon) will have a pearlite structure throughout the grains with no cementite at the boundaries.
[src:american-welding-society/carbon-steel] The relative amounts of constituents are found using the lever rule.
[src:american-welding-society/carbon-steel] Spheroidite can form at lower temperatures but the time needed drastically increases, as this is a diffusion-controlled process.
[src:american-welding-society/carbon-steel] The result is a structure of rods or spheres of cementite within primary structure (ferrite or pearlite, depending on which side of the eutectoid you are on).
[src:american-welding-society/carbon-steel] The purpose is to soften higher carbon steels and allow more formability.
[src:american-welding-society/carbon-steel] This is the softest and most ductile form of steel.
[src:american-welding-society/carbon-steel] might still exist in hypereutectoid steels).
[src:american-welding-society/carbon-steel] Usually it is just furnace cooled, where the furnace is turned off with the steel still inside.
[src:american-welding-society/carbon-steel] , with no internal stresses, which is often necessary for cost-effective forming.
[src:american-welding-society/carbon-steel] Only spheroidized steel is softer and more ductile.
[src:american-welding-society/carbon-steel] A process used to relieve stress in a cold-worked carbon steel with less than 0.3% C.
[src:american-welding-society/carbon-steel] The image above shows the process annealing area.
[src:american-welding-society/carbon-steel] It is a process in which hypoeutectoid steel is heated above the upper critical temperature.
[src:american-welding-society/carbon-steel] This temperature is maintained for a time and then reduced to below the lower critical temperature and is again maintained.
[src:american-welding-society/carbon-steel] This method eliminates any temperature gradient.
[src:american-welding-society/carbon-steel] Carbon steel is heated to the austenitic region, ensuring the steel completely transforms to austenite, and then slow cooling in air.
[src:american-welding-society/carbon-steel] Normalizing steel is most often done to refine the grain structure, increase the strength relative to annealed steel, and/or to provide more uniform internal structure.
[src:american-welding-society/carbon-steel] Carbon steel with at least 0.4 wt% C is heated to normalizing temperatures and then rapidly cooled (quenched) in water, brine, or oil to the critical temperature.
[src:american-welding-society/carbon-steel] The critical temperature is dependent on the carbon content, but as a general rule is lower as the carbon content increases.
[src:american-welding-society/carbon-steel] This results in a martensitic structure; a form of steel that possesses a super-saturated carbon content in a deformed body-centered cubic (BCC) crystalline structure, properly termed body-centered tetragonal (BCT), with much internal stress.
[src:american-welding-society/carbon-steel] , usually too brittle for practical purposes.
[src:american-welding-society/carbon-steel] These internal stresses may cause stress cracks on the surface.
[src:american-welding-society/carbon-steel] Quenched steel is approximately three times harder (four with more carbon) than normalized steel.
[src:american-welding-society/carbon-steel] It is a form of isothermal heat treatment applied after an initial quench, typically in a molten salt bath, at a temperature just above the "martensite start temperature".
[src:american-welding-society/carbon-steel] At this temperature, residual stresses within the material are relieved and some bainite may be formed from the retained austenite which did not have time to transform into anything else.
[src:american-welding-society/carbon-steel] In industry, this is a process used to control the ductility and hardness of a material.
[src:american-welding-society/carbon-steel] With longer marquenching, the ductility increases with a minimal loss in strength; the steel is held in this solution until the inner and outer temperatures of the part equalize.
[src:american-welding-society/carbon-steel] Then the steel is cooled at a moderate speed to keep the temperature gradient minimal.
[src:american-welding-society/carbon-steel] Not only does this process reduce internal stresses and stress cracks, but it also increases impact resistance.
[src:american-welding-society/carbon-steel] This is the most common heat treatment encountered because the final properties can be precisely determined by the temperature and time of the tempering.
[src:american-welding-society/carbon-steel] The elevated temperature allows very small amounts spheroidite to form, which restores ductility but reduces hardness.
[src:american-welding-society/carbon-steel] Actual temperatures and times are carefully chosen for each composition.
[src:american-welding-society/carbon-steel] The resulting steel, called bainite, produces an acicular microstructure in the steel that has great strength (but less than martensite), greater ductility, higher impact resistance, and less distortion than martensite steel.
[src:american-welding-society/carbon-steel] The disadvantage of austempering is it can be used only on a few sheets of steel, and it requires a special salt bath.
[src:american-welding-society/carbon-steel] Case hardening processes harden only the exterior of the steel part, creating a hard, wear-resistant skin (the "case") but preserving a tough and ductile interior.
[src:american-welding-society/carbon-steel] Carbon steels are not very hardenable meaning they can not be hardened throughout thick sections.
[src:american-welding-society/carbon-steel] Alloy steels have a better hardenability, so they can be through-hardened and do not require case hardening.
[src:american-welding-society/carbon-steel] This property of carbon steel can be beneficial, because it gives the surface good wear characteristics but leaves the core flexible and shock-absorbing.
[src:american-welding-society/cathodic-protection] Cathodic protection systems protect a wide range of metallic structures in various environments.
[src:american-welding-society/cathodic-protection] Common applications are: steel water or fuel pipelines and steel storage tanks such as home water heaters; steel pier piles; ship and boat hulls; offshore oil platforms and onshore oil well casings; offshore wind farm foundations and metal reinforcement bars in concrete buildings and structures.
[src:american-welding-society/cathodic-protection] Another common application is in galvanized steel, in which a sacrificial coating of zinc on steel parts protects them from rust.
[src:american-welding-society/cathodic-protection] Cathodic protection can, in some cases, prevent stress corrosion cracking.
[src:american-welding-society/cathodic-protection] Cathodic protection was first described by Sir Humphry Davy in a series of papers presented to the Royal Society in London in 1824.
[src:american-welding-society/cathodic-protection] The first application was to HMS *Samarang* in 1824.
[src:american-welding-society/cathodic-protection] Sacrificial anodes made from iron attached to the copper sheath of the hull below the waterline dramatically reduced the corrosion rate of the copper.
[src:american-welding-society/cathodic-protection] However, a side effect of cathodic protection was the increase in marine growth.
[src:american-welding-society/cathodic-protection] Usually, copper when corroding releases copper ions which have an anti-fouling effect.
[src:american-welding-society/cathodic-protection] Since excess marine growth affected the performance of the ship, the Royal Navy decided that it was better to allow the copper to corrode and have the benefit of reduced marine growth, so cathodic protection was not used further.
[src:american-welding-society/cathodic-protection] Davy was assisted in his experiments by his pupil Michael Faraday, who continued his research after Davy's death.
[src:american-welding-society/cathodic-protection] In 1834, Faraday discovered the quantitative connection between corrosion weight loss and electric current and thus laid the foundation for the future application of cathodic protection.
[src:american-welding-society/cathodic-protection] Thomas Edison experimented with impressed current cathodic protection on ships in 1890, but was unsuccessful due to the lack of a suitable current source and anode materials.
[src:american-welding-society/cathodic-protection] It would be 100 years after Davy's experiment before cathodic protection was used widely on oil pipelines in the United States—cathodic protection was applied to steel gas pipelines beginning in 1928 and more widely in the 1930s.
[src:american-welding-society/cathodic-protection] In the application of *passive* cathodic protection, a *galvanic anode*, a piece of a more electrochemically "active" metal (more negative electrode potential), is attached to the vulnerable metal surface where it is exposed to an electrolyte.
[src:american-welding-society/cathodic-protection] Galvanic anodes are selected because they have a more "active" voltage than the metal of the target structure (typically steel).
[src:american-welding-society/cathodic-protection] In this environment the steel reinforcement has a passive protective layer and remains largely stable.
[src:american-welding-society/cathodic-protection] Galvanic systems are "constant potential" systems that aim to restore the concrete's natural protective environment by providing a high initial current to restore passivity.
[src:american-welding-society/cathodic-protection] It then reverts to a lower sacrificial current, while harmful negative chloride ions migrate away from the steel and towards the positive anode.
[src:american-welding-society/cathodic-protection] The anodes remain reactive through their lifetime (10–20 years typically), increasing current when the resistivity decreases due to corrosion hazards such as rainfall, temperature increases, or flooding.
[src:american-welding-society/cathodic-protection] The reactive nature of these anodes makes them an efficient choice.
[src:american-welding-society/cathodic-protection] Unlike impressed current cathodic protection (ICCP) systems, steel constant polarization is not the goal, rather the restoration of the environment.
[src:american-welding-society/cathodic-protection] Polarization of the target structure is caused by the electron flow from the anode to the cathode, so the two metals must have a good electrically conductive contact.
[src:american-welding-society/cathodic-protection] The driving force for the cathodic protection current is the difference in electrode potential between the anode and the cathode.
[src:american-welding-society/cathodic-protection] During the initial phase of high current, the potential of the steel surface is polarized (pushed) more negative protecting the steel which hydroxide ion generation at the steel surface and ionic migration restore the concrete environment.
[src:american-welding-society/cathodic-protection] Over time the galvanic anode continues to corrode, consuming the anode material until eventually it must be replaced.
[src:american-welding-society/cathodic-protection] Galvanic or sacrificial anodes are made in various shapes and sizes using alloys of zinc, magnesium, and aluminium.
[src:american-welding-society/cathodic-protection] ASTM International publishes standards on the composition and manufacturing of galvanic anodes.
[src:american-welding-society/cathodic-protection] In order for galvanic cathodic protection to work, the anode must possess a lower (that is, more negative) electrode potential than that of the cathode (the target structure to be protected).
[src:american-welding-society/cathodic-protection] The table below shows a simplified galvanic series which is used to select the anode metal.
[src:american-welding-society/cathodic-protection] The anode must be chosen from a material that is lower on the list than the material to be protected.
[src:american-welding-society/cathodic-protection] In some cases, *impressed current cathodic protection* (ICCP) systems are used.
[src:american-welding-society/cathodic-protection] These consist of anodes connected to a DC power source, often a transformer-rectifier connected to AC power.
[src:american-welding-society/cathodic-protection] In the absence of an AC supply, alternative power sources may be used, such as solar panels, wind power or gas powered thermoelectric generators.
[src:american-welding-society/cathodic-protection] Anodes for ICCP systems are available in a variety of shapes and sizes.
[src:american-welding-society/cathodic-protection] Common anodes are tubular and solid rod shapes or continuous ribbons of various materials.
[src:american-welding-society/cathodic-protection] These include high silicon, cast iron, graphite, mixed metal oxide (MMO), platinum and niobium coated wire and other materials.
[src:american-welding-society/cathodic-protection] For pipelines, anodes are arranged in groundbeds either distributed or in a deep vertical hole depending on several design and field condition factors including current distribution requirements.
[src:american-welding-society/cathodic-protection] Cathodic protection transformer-rectifier units are often custom manufactured and equipped with a variety of features, including remote monitoring and control, integral current interrupters and various type of electrical enclosures.
[src:american-welding-society/cathodic-protection] The output DC negative terminal is connected to the structure to be protected by the cathodic protection system.
[src:american-welding-society/cathodic-protection] The rectifier output DC positive cable is connected to the anodes.
[src:american-welding-society/cathodic-protection] The AC power cable is connected to the rectifier input terminals.
[src:american-welding-society/cathodic-protection] The output of the ICCP system should be optimized to provide enough current to provide protection to the target structure.
[src:american-welding-society/cathodic-protection] Some cathodic protection transformer-rectifier units are designed with taps on the transformer windings and jumper terminals to select the voltage output of the ICCP system.
[src:american-welding-society/cathodic-protection] Cathodic protection transformer-rectifier units for water tanks and used in other applications are made with solid state circuits to automatically adjust the operating voltage to maintain the optimum current output or structure-to-electrolyte potential.
[src:american-welding-society/cathodic-protection] Analog or digital meters are often installed to show the operating voltages (DC and sometimes AC) and current output.
[src:american-welding-society/cathodic-protection] For shore structures and other large complex target structures, ICCP systems are often designed with multiple independent zones of anodes with separate cathodic protection transformer-rectifier circuits.
[src:american-welding-society/cathodic-protection] Hybrid systems use a combination of the aforementioned systems to achieve some of the benefits of both, utilizing the restorative capabilities of ICCP systems but maintaining the reactive, lower cost, and easier-to-maintain nature of a galvanic anode.
[src:american-welding-society/cathodic-protection] The system is made up of wired galvanic anodes in arrays typically 400 millimetres (16 in) apart, which are then initially powered for a short period to restore the concrete and to power ionic migration.
[src:american-welding-society/cathodic-protection] The power supply is then taken away and the anodes are simply attached to the steel as a galvanic system.
[src:american-welding-society/cathodic-protection] More powered phases can be administered if needed.
[src:american-welding-society/cathodic-protection] Like galvanic systems, corrosion rate monitoring from polarization tests and half-cell potential mapping can be used to measure corrosion.
[src:american-welding-society/cathodic-protection] Polarization is not the goal for the life of the system.
[src:american-welding-society/cathodic-protection] This technology is also used to protect water heaters.
[src:american-welding-society/cathodic-protection] The electrons sent by the imposed current anode (composed of titanium and covered with MMO) prevent the inside of the tank from rusting.
[src:american-welding-society/cathodic-protection] In order to be recognized as effective, these anodes must comply with certain standards: A cathodic protection system is considered efficient when its potential reaches or exceeds the limits established by the cathodic protection criteria.
[src:american-welding-society/cathodic-protection] The cathode protection criteria used come from the standard NACE SP0388-2007 (formerly RP0388-2001) of the NACE National Association of Corrosion Engineers.
[src:american-welding-society/cathodic-protection] Hazardous product pipelines are routinely protected by a coating supplemented with cathodic protection.
[src:american-welding-society/cathodic-protection] An impressed current cathodic protection system (ICCP) for a pipeline consists of a DC power source, often an AC powered transformer rectifier and an anode, or array of anodes buried in the ground (the anode groundbed).
[src:american-welding-society/cathodic-protection] The DC power source would typically have a DC output of up to 50 amperes and 50 volts, but this depends on several factors, such as the size of the pipeline and coating quality.
[src:american-welding-society/cathodic-protection] The positive DC output terminal would be connected via cables to the anode array, while another cable would connect the negative terminal of the rectifier to the pipeline, preferably through junction boxes to allow measurements to be taken.
[src:american-welding-society/cathodic-protection] Anodes can be installed in a groundbed consisting of a vertical hole backfilled with conductive coke (a material that improves the performance and life of the anodes) or laid in a prepared trench, surrounded by conductive coke and backfilled.
[src:american-welding-society/cathodic-protection] The choice of groundbed type and size depends on the application, location and soil resistivity.
[src:american-welding-society/cathodic-protection] The DC cathodic protection current is then adjusted to the optimum level after conducting various tests including measurements of pipe-to-soil potentials or electrode potential.
[src:american-welding-society/cathodic-protection] When designing the system, and periodically after installation, engineers will conduct a baseline measurement campaign, during which all existing active protection systems in the area will be switched off (or as many as possible) and the *native* or *natural* pipe-to-electrode potential is recorded.
[src:american-welding-society/cathodic-protection] This measurement will provide clues about how the pipeline can be sectioned into electrical systems, how many anodes and rectifiers will be needed and where they should be placed.
[src:american-welding-society/cathodic-protection] It is sometimes more economically viable to protect a pipeline using galvanic (sacrificial) anodes.
[src:american-welding-society/cathodic-protection] This is often the case on smaller diameter pipelines of limited length.
[src:american-welding-society/cathodic-protection] Galvanic anodes rely on the galvanic series potentials of the metals to drive cathodic protection current from the anode to the structure being protected.
[src:american-welding-society/cathodic-protection] Water pipelines of various pipe materials are also provided with cathodic protection where owners determine the cost is reasonable for the expected pipeline service life extension attributed to the application of cathodic protection.
[src:american-welding-society/cathodic-protection] Cathodic protection on ships is often implemented by galvanic anodes attached to the hull and ICCP for larger vessels.
[src:american-welding-society/cathodic-protection] Since ships are regularly removed from the water for inspections and maintenance, it is a simple task to replace the galvanic anodes.
[src:american-welding-society/cathodic-protection] Galvanic anodes are generally shaped to reduced drag in the water and fitted flush to the hull to also try to minimize drag.
[src:american-welding-society/cathodic-protection] Smaller vessels, with non-metallic hulls, such as yachts, are equipped with galvanic anodes to protect areas such as outboard motors.
[src:american-welding-society/cathodic-protection] As with all galvanic cathodic protection, this application relies on a solid electrical connection between the anode and the item to be protected.
[src:american-welding-society/cathodic-protection] For ICCP on ships, the anodes are usually constructed of a relatively inert material such as platinized titanium.
[src:american-welding-society/cathodic-protection] A DC power supply is provided within the ship and the anodes mounted on the outside of the hull.
[src:american-welding-society/cathodic-protection] The anode cables are introduced into the ship via a compression seal fitting and routed to the DC power source.
[src:american-welding-society/cathodic-protection] The negative cable from the power supply is simply attached to the hull to complete the circuit.
[src:american-welding-society/cathodic-protection] Ship ICCP anodes are flush-mounted, minimizing the effects of drag on the ship, and located a minimum 5 ft below the light load line in an area to avoid mechanical damage.
[src:american-welding-society/cathodic-protection] The current density required for protection is a function of velocity and considered when selecting the current capacity and location of anode placement on the hull.
[src:american-welding-society/cathodic-protection] Some ships may require specialist treatment, for example aluminium hulls with steel fixtures will create an electrochemical cell where the aluminium hull can act as a galvanic anode and corrosion is enhanced.
[src:american-welding-society/cathodic-protection] In cases like this, aluminium or zinc galvanic anodes can be used to offset the potential difference between the aluminium hull and the steel fixture.
[src:american-welding-society/cathodic-protection] If the steel fixtures are large, several galvanic anodes may be required, or even a small ICCP system.
[src:american-welding-society/cathodic-protection] Marine cathodic protection covers many areas, jetties, harbors, offshore structures.
[src:american-welding-society/cathodic-protection] The variety of different types of structure leads to a variety of systems to provide protection.
[src:american-welding-society/cathodic-protection] Galvanic anodes are favored, but ICCP can also often be used.
[src:american-welding-society/cathodic-protection] Because of the wide variety of structure geometry, composition, and architecture, specialized firms are often required to engineer structure-specific cathodic protection systems.
[src:american-welding-society/cathodic-protection] The application to concrete reinforcement is slightly different in that the anodes and reference electrodes are usually embedded in the concrete at the time of construction when the concrete is being poured.
[src:american-welding-society/cathodic-protection] For ICCP, the principle is the same as any other ICCP system.
[src:american-welding-society/cathodic-protection] However, in a typical atmospherically exposed concrete structure such as a bridge, there will be many more anodes distributed through the structure as opposed to an array of anodes as used on a pipeline.
[src:american-welding-society/cathodic-protection] This makes for a more complicated system and usually an automatically controlled DC power source is used, possibly with an option for remote monitoring and operation.
[src:american-welding-society/cathodic-protection] For buried or submerged structures, the treatment is similar to that of any other buried or submerged structure.
[src:american-welding-society/cathodic-protection] Galvanic systems offer the advantage of being easier to retrofit and do not need any control systems as ICCP does.
[src:american-welding-society/cathodic-protection] For pipelines constructed from pre-stressed concrete cylinder pipe (PCCP), the techniques used for cathodic protection are generally as for steel pipelines except that the applied potential must be limited to prevent damage to the prestressing wire.
[src:american-welding-society/cathodic-protection] The steel wire in a PCCP pipeline is stressed to the point that any corrosion of the wire can result in failure.
[src:american-welding-society/cathodic-protection] An additional problem is that any excessive hydrogen ions as a result of an excessively negative potential can cause hydrogen embrittlement of the wire, also resulting in failure.
[src:american-welding-society/cathodic-protection] The failure of too many wires will result in catastrophic failure of the PCCP.
[src:american-welding-society/cathodic-protection] To implement ICCP therefore requires very careful control to ensure satisfactory protection.
[src:american-welding-society/cathodic-protection] A simpler option is to use galvanic anodes, which are self-limiting and need no control.
[src:american-welding-society/cathodic-protection] Vessels, pipelines and tanks (including ballast tanks) which are used to store or transport liquids can also be protected from corrosion on their internal surfaces by the use of cathodic protection.
[src:american-welding-society/cathodic-protection] A common application of internal cathodic protection is water storage tanks and power plant shell and tube heat exchangers.
[src:american-welding-society/cathodic-protection] Galvanizing generally refers to hot-dip galvanizing which is a way of coating steel with a layer of metallic zinc or tin.
[src:american-welding-society/cathodic-protection] Lead or antimony are often added to the molten zinc bath, and also other metals have been studied.
[src:american-welding-society/cathodic-protection] Galvanized coatings are quite durable in most environments because they combine the barrier properties of a coating with some of the benefits of cathodic protection.
[src:american-welding-society/cathodic-protection] If the zinc coating is scratched or otherwise locally damaged and steel is exposed, the surrounding areas of zinc coating form a galvanic cell with the exposed steel and protect it from corrosion.
[src:american-welding-society/cathodic-protection] This is a form of localized cathodic protection - the zinc acts as a sacrificial anode.
[src:american-welding-society/cathodic-protection] Galvanizing, while using the electrochemical principle of cathodic protection, is not actually cathodic but sacrificial protection.
[src:american-welding-society/cathodic-protection] In the case of galvanizing, only areas very close to the zinc are protected.
[src:american-welding-society/cathodic-protection] Hence, a larger area of bare steel would only be protected around the edges.
[src:american-welding-society/cathodic-protection] Several companies market electronic devices claiming to mitigate corrosion for automobiles and trucks.
[src:american-welding-society/cathodic-protection] Corrosion control professionals find they do not work.
[src:american-welding-society/cathodic-protection] There is no peer reviewed scientific testing and validation supporting the use of the devices.
[src:american-welding-society/cathodic-protection] Under section 74.01(1) (b) of the *Competition Act Canada*, no performance claims about a product or its effectiveness can be done unless it can be proven that they are based on adequate and proper tests.
[src:american-welding-society/cathodic-protection] The Competition Bureau Canada proceeded to investigate several companies selling electronic corrosion devices in Canada.
[src:american-welding-society/cathodic-protection] Some were forced to withdraw their product from the market as they could not support their claims scientifically.
[src:american-welding-society/cathodic-protection] Electrode potential is measured with reference electrodes.
[src:american-welding-society/cathodic-protection] Copper–copper sulphate electrodes are used for structures in contact with soil or fresh water.
[src:american-welding-society/cathodic-protection] Silver/silver chloride/seawater electrodes or pure zinc electrodes are used for seawater applications.
[src:american-welding-society/cathodic-protection] The methods are described in EN 13509:2003 and NACE TM0497 along with the sources of error in the voltage that appears on the display of the meter.
[src:american-welding-society/cathodic-protection] Interpretation of electrode potential measurements to determine the potential at the interface between the anode of the corrosion cell and the electrolyte requires training and cannot be expected to match the accuracy of measurements done in laboratory work.
[src:american-welding-society/cathodic-protection] A side effect of improperly applied cathodic protection is the production of atomic hydrogen, leading to its absorption in the protected metal and subsequent hydrogen embrittlement of welds and materials with high hardness.
[src:american-welding-society/cathodic-protection] Under normal conditions, the atomic hydrogen will combine at the metal surface to create hydrogen gas, which cannot penetrate the metal.
[src:american-welding-society/cathodic-protection] Hydrogen atoms, however, are small enough to pass through the crystalline steel structure, and can lead in some cases to hydrogen embrittlement.
[src:american-welding-society/cathodic-protection] This is a process of disbondment of protective coatings from the protected structure (cathode) due to the formation of hydrogen ions over the surface of the protected material (cathode).
[src:american-welding-society/cathodic-protection] Disbonding can be exacerbated by an increase in alkali ions and an increase in cathodic polarization.
[src:american-welding-society/cathodic-protection] The degree of disbonding is also reliant on the type of coating, with some coatings affected more than others.
[src:american-welding-society/cathodic-protection] Cathodic protection systems should be operated so that the structure does not become excessively polarized, since this also promotes disbonding due to excessively negative potentials.
[src:american-welding-society/cathodic-protection] Cathodic disbonding occurs rapidly in pipelines that contain hot fluids because the process is accelerated by heat flow.
[src:american-welding-society/cathodic-protection] Effectiveness of cathodic protection (CP) systems on steel pipelines can be impaired by the use of solid film backed dielectric coatings such as polyethylene tapes, shrinkable pipeline sleeves, and factory applied single or multiple solid film coatings.
[src:american-welding-society/cathodic-protection] This phenomenon occurs because of the high electrical resistivity of these film backings.
[src:american-welding-society/cathodic-protection] Protective electric current from the cathodic protection system is blocked or shielded from reaching the underlying metal by the highly resistive film backing.
[src:american-welding-society/cathodic-protection] Cathodic shielding was first defined in the 1980s as being a problem, and technical papers on the subject have been regularly published since then.
[src:american-welding-society/cathodic-protection] Cathodic shielding is referenced in a number of the standards listed below.
[src:american-welding-society/cathodic-protection] In many countries, having a related CP certificate is recommended or, in some cases, mandatory for doing a CP job, from field test to design.
[src:american-welding-society/cathodic-protection] There are different certification bodies and evaluation methods, but two of them are more common: AMPP certification and ISO 15257.
[src:american-welding-society/cathodic-protection] AMPP cathodic protection certification has four levels: Tester, Technician, Technologist, and Specialist.
[src:american-welding-society/cathodic-protection] ISO 15257 has five levels: Four levels close to the AMPP definition, plus another level for those who have made a scientific contribution.
[src:american-welding-society/cathodic-protection] The main center for cathodic protection certification in France and some French language countries is CEFRACOR.
[src:american-welding-society/cathodic-protection] fkks cert GmbH (owned by fkks: Fachverband Kathodischer Korrosionsschutz e.V., trans.
[src:american-welding-society/cathodic-protection] German Professional Association for Cathodic Protection specialists) is an accredited certification scheme in the field of cathodic corrosion protection.
[src:american-welding-society/cathodic-protection] Three different bodies will provide cathodic protection certificates based on ISO 15257: APCERT, CICPND, and RINA.
[src:american-welding-society/cathodic-protection] Institute of Corrosion (ICorr), Corrosion Prevention Association (CPA), and TWI offer a Cathodic Protection, Training, Assessment, and Certification Scheme that evaluates the competence levels of cathodic protection personnel.
[src:american-welding-society/cathodic-protection] Moreover, AMPP is highly active and known in the Middle East.
[src:american-welding-society/comfort-a-adams] Adams was born in Cleveland, Ohio to Comfort Avery Adams Sr. and Katherine Emily Peticolas on November 1, 1868.
[src:american-welding-society/comfort-a-adams] "Doc Adams", as he was commonly addressed by his colleagues and friends, received his Honorary Doctorate of Engineering from his alma mater, Case School of Applied Science, in 1925 after having been on the faculty at Harvard College and dean of their engineering school for almost 35 years.
[src:american-welding-society/comfort-a-adams] He later received his second honorary doctorate from Lehigh University in 1939.
[src:american-welding-society/comfort-a-adams] By that time he had retired from Harvard.
[src:american-welding-society/comfort-a-adams] In terms of an all-around American engineer in the early 20th century, Comfort A.
[src:american-welding-society/comfort-a-adams] Adams comes the closest to being America's answer to Britain's I.
[src:american-welding-society/comfort-a-adams] Adams was president of the American Institute of Electrical Engineers and the American Welding Society.
[src:american-welding-society/comfort-a-adams] He organized and chaired the Welding Research Council.
[src:american-welding-society/comfort-a-adams] Adams married Elizabeth Chassis Parsons in 1894, and they adopted two children.
[src:american-welding-society/comfort-a-adams] Adams died at his home in Philadelphia, Pennsylvania on February 21, 1958.
